WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.503 --> 00:00:05.375
(gentle operatic music)

2
00:00:15.487 --> 00:00:17.827
<v Voiceover>She actually saw a light,</v>

3
00:00:17.827 --> 00:00:19.624
a white light enter her body.

4
00:00:19.624 --> 00:00:22.146
<v Voiceover>And from the middle of the light</v>

5
00:00:22.146 --> 00:00:24.450
came the words, "You are healed."

6
00:00:26.982 --> 00:00:29.738 line:15% 
<v Voiceover>A force just took a hold of me.</v>

7
00:00:29.738 --> 00:00:31.861
It lifted me up off my feet.

8
00:00:34.419 --> 00:00:36.499 line:15% 
<v Voiceover>And as I was looking at her I mean</v>

9
00:00:36.499 --> 00:00:38.255
she just radiated light.

10
00:00:39.047 --> 00:00:41.172
(sparkling)

11
00:00:41.172 --> 00:00:42.784
<v Voiceover>And there seemed to be a person</v>

12
00:00:42.784 --> 00:00:44.848
or force standing in the doorway.

13
00:00:44.848 --> 00:00:47.488
To prevent me from entering.

14
00:00:48.990 --> 00:00:51.810
<v Voiceover>It was just a wonderful miracle.</v>

15
00:00:53.420 --> 00:00:54.590
<v Voiceover>What comes to mind</v>

16
00:00:54.590 --> 00:00:56.990
when you hear the word miracle?

17
00:00:56.990 --> 00:00:58.970
Incredible coincidence?

18
00:00:58.970 --> 00:01:01.400
The power of mind over matter?

19
00:01:01.400 --> 00:01:03.830
Biblical stories like those of the burning bush,

20
00:01:03.830 --> 00:01:06.000
or the parting of the Red Sea?

21
00:01:06.590 --> 00:01:09.090
What do we mean by a miracle anyway?

22
00:01:09.890 --> 00:01:12.082
A miracle is something that appears to be

23
00:01:12.082 --> 00:01:14.600
unexplainable by the laws of nature,

24
00:01:14.600 --> 00:01:17.300
and so is thought to be supernatural in origin,

25
00:01:17.300 --> 00:01:19.020
or an act of God.

26
00:01:19.520 --> 00:01:20.670
Webster said that.

27
00:01:20.990 --> 00:01:23.420
Unexplainable by the laws of nature.

28
00:01:23.420 --> 00:01:24.920
<v ->Just like hundreds of years ago,</v>

29
00:01:25.526 --> 00:01:28.556
no one would imagine a man walking on the moon,

30
00:01:28.556 --> 00:01:30.986
if they saw it they would call it a miracle.

31
00:01:30.986 --> 00:01:33.476
Maybe in 500 years the miracles that we see

32
00:01:33.476 --> 00:01:35.338
every single day that we can't explain

33
00:01:35.338 --> 00:01:37.046
will be explainable.

34
00:01:37.046 --> 00:01:39.236
<v ->I don't like to use words like miracle,</v>

35
00:01:39.236 --> 00:01:40.826
or spontaneous remission,

36
00:01:40.826 --> 00:01:44.426
because they lead you away from research.

37
00:01:44.426 --> 00:01:46.826
You don't do research on miracles.

38
00:01:46.826 --> 00:01:48.596
I mean if somebody goes to Lourde's

39
00:01:48.596 --> 00:01:50.248
and their cancer disappears,

40
00:01:50.248 --> 00:01:52.946
and we have evidence of certain cases,

41
00:01:52.946 --> 00:01:55.676
you'd say, "Well he went to Lourde's that's a miracle."

42
00:01:55.676 --> 00:01:58.526
But I'd rather take all the people who went to Lourde's,

43
00:01:58.526 --> 00:01:59.460
sit 'em down and say,

44
00:01:59.460 --> 00:02:02.550
"Fill out this form, and tell me

45
00:02:02.550 --> 00:02:05.490
"what you did, why you think it happened,

46
00:02:05.490 --> 00:02:07.502
"how did you get to Lourde's?

47
00:02:07.502 --> 00:02:08.760
"You take a train or an airplane?"

48
00:02:08.760 --> 00:02:10.470
You know, let's look at all these facts,

49
00:02:10.470 --> 00:02:12.060
so that when the next person says,

50
00:02:12.060 --> 00:02:13.470
"I have an incurable disease."

51
00:02:13.470 --> 00:02:14.670
You say, "Look, here's the list,

52
00:02:14.670 --> 00:02:16.530
"maybe you wanna go to Lourde's."

53
00:02:16.530 --> 00:02:19.170
<v Voiceover>So when we hear contemporary stories</v>

54
00:02:19.170 --> 00:02:22.262
that seem to be unexplainable by the laws of nature,

55
00:02:22.262 --> 00:02:25.382
we have to ask, "Are these miracles?"

56
00:02:25.382 --> 00:02:27.720
To shed some light on these mysterious happenings,

57
00:02:27.720 --> 00:02:29.640
and how they affect lives,

58
00:02:29.640 --> 00:02:31.770
we'll look into some contemporary accounts

59
00:02:31.770 --> 00:02:35.440
from people who believe that miracles do happen.

60
00:02:35.940 --> 00:02:37.416
We'll hear in their own words,

61
00:02:37.416 --> 00:02:40.274
their personal stories of miracles.

62
00:02:41.254 --> 00:02:45.844
(gentle music)

63
00:02:45.844 --> 00:02:48.244
Joan Wester Anderson, a magazine journalist,

64
00:02:48.244 --> 00:02:52.024
and author, says she experienced a miracle firsthand,

65
00:02:52.024 --> 00:02:53.946
and went on to investigate other stories

66
00:02:53.946 --> 00:02:55.774
that were then published in her book,

67
00:02:55.774 --> 00:02:57.496
Where Miracles Happen.

68
00:02:58.024 --> 00:03:00.036
<v ->I had this image of miracles as happening</v>

69
00:03:00.036 --> 00:03:02.644
in huge shrines, or to very special people,

70
00:03:02.644 --> 00:03:04.624 line:15% 
or perhaps things that happened

71
00:03:04.624 --> 00:03:06.784 line:15% 
years and years and years ago.

72
00:03:06.784 --> 00:03:10.026
But certainly not today, to ordinary people.

73
00:03:12.246 --> 00:03:15.349
But one day I was out raking our leaves

74
00:03:15.349 --> 00:03:18.529
in the back yard, stuffing bags full of them,

75
00:03:18.529 --> 00:03:20.059
when all of a sudden I look down

76
00:03:20.059 --> 00:03:22.309
and realized, in horror, that my wedding

77
00:03:22.309 --> 00:03:24.633
and engagement rings were not on my finger.

78
00:03:28.603 --> 00:03:30.591
When I looked at the back yard I realized

79
00:03:30.591 --> 00:03:32.831
they had to be out here somewhere,

80
00:03:32.831 --> 00:03:35.211
but there was absolutely no way that I was

81
00:03:35.211 --> 00:03:37.085
ever going to find them.

82
00:03:38.151 --> 00:03:39.887
And just then a friend of mine stepped

83
00:03:39.887 --> 00:03:42.519
through the hedge which divided our two properties,

84
00:03:42.519 --> 00:03:44.899
and I didn't know her real well

85
00:03:44.899 --> 00:03:48.541
at that time, and she trudged across the leaves and said,

86
00:03:48.541 --> 00:03:50.023
"What's wrong?"

87
00:03:50.023 --> 00:03:52.067
She could tell and I held up my hand and said,

88
00:03:52.067 --> 00:03:54.251
"I've lost my rings out here."

89
00:03:54.393 --> 00:03:56.323
And she said, "Well let's pray about it."

90
00:03:56.323 --> 00:03:58.787
She grabbed my hand, and pushed me down

91
00:03:58.787 --> 00:04:00.747
in the leaves to a kneeling position, I'm thinking,

92
00:04:01.907 --> 00:04:03.883
"What if someone's looking out the window

93
00:04:03.883 --> 00:04:05.199
"and sees us doing this?"

94
00:04:05.199 --> 00:04:07.803
But at the same time it seemed so nice.

95
00:04:09.433 --> 00:04:11.513
And she began to talk to God about it,

96
00:04:11.513 --> 00:04:13.781
she just said, "God we need a miracle,

97
00:04:13.781 --> 00:04:15.517
"we have to find the rings, they're out here

98
00:04:15.517 --> 00:04:17.113
"and you know where they are."

99
00:04:17.113 --> 00:04:20.417
And then she kinda stopped,

100
00:04:20.417 --> 00:04:22.855
and I thought, "Well now that was really nice of her."

101
00:04:22.855 --> 00:04:24.393
But not for a minute did I think anything

102
00:04:24.393 --> 00:04:26.269
was going to happen.

103
00:04:26.269 --> 00:04:29.603
She got up, she started walking across the lawn

104
00:04:29.603 --> 00:04:32.149
and she went around a huge pile

105
00:04:32.149 --> 00:04:34.949
and then stopped, as if she was listening almost,

106
00:04:34.949 --> 00:04:37.527
and then she took a couple more steps,

107
00:04:37.527 --> 00:04:39.485
stopped in front of another pile,

108
00:04:39.485 --> 00:04:41.585
reached down and pulled out both my rings,

109
00:04:41.585 --> 00:04:43.435
now they were not connected.

110
00:04:43.435 --> 00:04:45.113
The very fact that they were both there,

111
00:04:45.113 --> 00:04:47.773
and she pulled them both up and said,

112
00:04:47.773 --> 00:04:49.145
"Here they are."

113
00:04:49.145 --> 00:04:51.497
Just as if she wasn't even surprised.

114
00:04:51.497 --> 00:04:52.701
How did you do that?

115
00:04:52.701 --> 00:04:53.681
And she said,

116
00:04:53.681 --> 00:04:56.341
"I didn't do it, God did it.

117
00:04:56.341 --> 00:04:58.525
"He told me where to look."

118
00:04:58.525 --> 00:05:01.017
And from that time on, I began to change

119
00:05:01.017 --> 00:05:03.733
my perspective of what a miracle was.

120
00:05:03.733 --> 00:05:06.673
When you put them in a framework that people

121
00:05:06.673 --> 00:05:09.781
can identify with, then you find that

122
00:05:09.781 --> 00:05:11.379
a lot of people say,

123
00:05:11.379 --> 00:05:14.791
"Oh, well I've had a miracle."

124
00:05:16.277 --> 00:05:21.121
(wind blowing)

125
00:05:22.521 --> 00:05:24.481
<v Voiceover>I was in the shower, kind of listening</v>

126
00:05:24.481 --> 00:05:27.729
to the pager and my tones went off.

127
00:05:27.729 --> 00:05:30.557
It came across as a car fire.

128
00:05:30.557 --> 00:05:33.385
<v Voiceover>Marker 37, car on fire.</v>

129
00:05:33.385 --> 00:05:34.841
<v ->I felt such a urgency,</v>

130
00:05:34.841 --> 00:05:37.895
like I've never experienced before.

131
00:05:37.895 --> 00:05:39.993
I felt like I had hands on my back

132
00:05:39.993 --> 00:05:42.683
just pushing me, and I needed to get out,

133
00:05:42.683 --> 00:05:45.565
I needed to hurry up and get to the scene.

134
00:05:45.565 --> 00:05:47.217
<v Voiceover>Mary Mueller, a firefighter,</v>

135
00:05:47.217 --> 00:05:48.983
was the first emergency worker to arrive

136
00:05:48.983 --> 00:05:51.921
at the scene of a tragic automobile accident.

137
00:05:51.921 --> 00:05:53.741
What happened next is described by

138
00:05:53.741 --> 00:05:56.541
Joan Wester Anderson, who included Mary's story

139
00:05:56.541 --> 00:05:58.137
in her book.

140
00:05:58.137 --> 00:05:59.371
<v ->Now the ironic part here was</v>

141
00:05:59.371 --> 00:06:02.169
that there was no fire, ultimately,

142
00:06:02.169 --> 00:06:03.849
but the first call that came in

143
00:06:03.849 --> 00:06:05.669
summoned firefighters because it was

144
00:06:05.669 --> 00:06:07.321
an incorrect call.

145
00:06:07.321 --> 00:06:09.729 line:15% 
<v ->I got within couple hundred feet</v>

146
00:06:09.729 --> 00:06:13.287 line:15% 
of the scene itself, and I just couldn't imagine

147
00:06:13.287 --> 00:06:16.335 line:15% 
what had happened here.

148
00:06:16.785 --> 00:06:19.361
It seemed like a car bomb had gone off,

149
00:06:19.361 --> 00:06:21.125
it was just complete devastation,

150
00:06:21.125 --> 00:06:23.981
there was tires all over from one side of the road

151
00:06:23.981 --> 00:06:25.719
to the other, out in the field.

152
00:06:25.719 --> 00:06:28.349
There was the top of the vehicle had been

153
00:06:28.349 --> 00:06:30.841
peeled open like a can opener.

154
00:06:30.841 --> 00:06:34.173
At this point, I looked down into the ditch area,

155
00:06:34.173 --> 00:06:36.609
and I saw a body down there.

156
00:06:36.609 --> 00:06:39.045
<v ->She slid down the snow on her knees</v>

157
00:06:39.045 --> 00:06:40.847
to this woman and discovered that she was

158
00:06:40.847 --> 00:06:43.647
bleeding to death from a massive wound.

159
00:06:43.647 --> 00:06:46.895
Mary had nothing to stem the blood

160
00:06:46.895 --> 00:06:49.863
except her firefighter's gloves.

161
00:06:49.863 --> 00:06:51.879
But they were covered with soot,

162
00:06:51.879 --> 00:06:54.579
and she felt, "I can't put that on this

163
00:06:54.579 --> 00:06:56.819
"young woman's head, because I'll introduce

164
00:06:56.819 --> 00:06:58.359
"so much infection."

165
00:06:58.359 --> 00:07:01.621
<v ->And I knew that I needed something really quick.</v>

166
00:07:01.621 --> 00:07:03.861
And there was no medical help around,

167
00:07:03.861 --> 00:07:05.597
and I had nothing.

168
00:07:05.597 --> 00:07:08.369
And in a split second that I looked over to my left

169
00:07:08.369 --> 00:07:11.311
at the car, and I looked over to the right

170
00:07:11.311 --> 00:07:14.221
at the bystanders who were a good distance

171
00:07:14.221 --> 00:07:17.471
away from me, I just reached way down

172
00:07:17.471 --> 00:07:19.429
in my heart and I said,

173
00:07:19.429 --> 00:07:21.669
"God, I really need some help here.

174
00:07:21.669 --> 00:07:26.075
"I'm gonna lose this girl, I can't do this by myself."

175
00:07:26.075 --> 00:07:28.287
And in that split second,

176
00:07:28.287 --> 00:07:31.927
a reddish color medical bag showed up

177
00:07:31.927 --> 00:07:35.371
approximately 12 inches off of my left knee.

178
00:07:35.371 --> 00:07:37.275
<v ->There were no footprints around it</v>

179
00:07:37.275 --> 00:07:39.683
in the snow, there was no way that it could've appeared,

180
00:07:39.683 --> 00:07:41.699
but there it was, and she said,

181
00:07:41.699 --> 00:07:43.885
"I didn't even have time to wonder at it,

182
00:07:43.885 --> 00:07:46.291
"I clicked it open, it had everything I needed,

183
00:07:46.291 --> 00:07:48.727
"all the white gauze, pads, everything sterile."

184
00:07:48.727 --> 00:07:51.891
And she began to take these out

185
00:07:51.891 --> 00:07:54.439
and just use them one after another.

186
00:07:54.439 --> 00:07:56.539
<v ->But when the EMS personnel did get there</v>

187
00:07:56.539 --> 00:07:59.227
the ambulance crew, paramedics, they came down

188
00:07:59.227 --> 00:08:03.231
and at this point, I was out of bandages

189
00:08:03.231 --> 00:08:06.255
in the bag itself, they were all gone.

190
00:08:06.255 --> 00:08:07.683
And it was perfect timing,

191
00:08:07.683 --> 00:08:09.923
they got there, they did their assessment

192
00:08:09.923 --> 00:08:11.631
after I told 'em what I had had,

193
00:08:11.631 --> 00:08:13.031
just to verify things,

194
00:08:13.031 --> 00:08:16.475
and the paramedic kind of pulled my hand up

195
00:08:16.475 --> 00:08:19.135
just a little bit to take a peek at the injury,

196
00:08:19.135 --> 00:08:21.515
and he put my hand right back down

197
00:08:21.515 --> 00:08:23.391
and he kinda whispered into my ear

198
00:08:23.391 --> 00:08:26.723
so not to upset the victim, he says,

199
00:08:26.723 --> 00:08:28.627
"Mary, you're holding this girl's life in your hands,

200
00:08:28.627 --> 00:08:30.447
"don't let go."

201
00:08:30.447 --> 00:08:32.493
And I'm like, "Oh boy, this is a heavy job."

202
00:08:32.493 --> 00:08:33.527
(laughs)

203
00:08:33.527 --> 00:08:35.993
So, I kept the pressure on the best I could,

204
00:08:35.993 --> 00:08:39.043
and because the severity, they taped my hands

205
00:08:39.043 --> 00:08:41.815
to her head to keep the pressure on,

206
00:08:41.815 --> 00:08:45.287
and then they taped both of us to the back board.

207
00:08:46.807 --> 00:08:48.451
<v ->Took them to the hospital</v>

208
00:08:48.451 --> 00:08:50.439
and the girl recovered eventually.

209
00:08:50.439 --> 00:08:54.023
About an hour or two later, Mary left the hospital

210
00:08:54.023 --> 00:08:55.843
and went back to the scene,

211
00:08:55.843 --> 00:08:58.839
to recover that mysterious medical bag.

212
00:08:58.839 --> 00:09:01.415
<v Voiceover>Mary found no evidence of the mysterious bag,</v>

213
00:09:01.415 --> 00:09:05.027
no discarded bandages, no sterile wrappers.

214
00:09:05.027 --> 00:09:06.959
The bag had vanished.

215
00:09:06.959 --> 00:09:08.695
<v ->The bag was gone,</v>

216
00:09:08.695 --> 00:09:10.459
and I said, "Well who cleaned this up?"

217
00:09:10.459 --> 00:09:12.055
And they said, "Nobody cleaned it up,

218
00:09:12.055 --> 00:09:14.855
"we thought you took it with you."

219
00:09:14.855 --> 00:09:16.957
I said, "I couldn't have my hands were taped

220
00:09:16.957 --> 00:09:18.691
"to this girl's head."

221
00:09:18.691 --> 00:09:19.791
And um...

222
00:09:20.651 --> 00:09:22.313
Made many inquiries,

223
00:09:22.313 --> 00:09:25.057
had many questions, and they all

224
00:09:25.057 --> 00:09:27.689
just came back to nobody knows where it came from

225
00:09:27.689 --> 00:09:30.359
and we haven't seen it since

226
00:09:30.359 --> 00:09:32.207
after that scene.

227
00:09:32.207 --> 00:09:34.109
It's gone.

228
00:09:36.043 --> 00:09:40.327
(calm music)

229
00:09:40.327 --> 00:09:41.853
(wind howling)

230
00:09:41.853 --> 00:09:43.895
<v Voiceover>Paul Robert Walker, author of</v>

231
00:09:43.895 --> 00:09:47.031
Every Day's A Miracle, also began his research

232
00:09:47.031 --> 00:09:50.282
as a result of a personal story.

233
00:09:50.282 --> 00:09:51.628
<v ->I was eager to do the book,</v>

234
00:09:51.628 --> 00:09:54.232 line:15% 
but I wasn't quite sure how to get into it,

235
00:09:54.232 --> 00:09:56.834 line:15% 
how to approach it, I wanted to tell the stories

236
00:09:56.834 --> 00:09:59.008
with an authenticity and an honesty,

237
00:09:59.008 --> 00:10:00.324
and a humanity.

238
00:10:00.324 --> 00:10:01.752
And I was thinking about it,

239
00:10:01.752 --> 00:10:03.964
I realized, that I have been living with my own

240
00:10:03.964 --> 00:10:06.930
miracle story for as long as I could remember.

241
00:10:06.930 --> 00:10:09.564
And it was really very much a part of my life.

242
00:10:09.564 --> 00:10:12.336
My story, it really began with my mother,

243
00:10:12.336 --> 00:10:14.324
it's my mother's story.

244
00:10:14.324 --> 00:10:16.340
My mother and father had been married for about

245
00:10:16.340 --> 00:10:19.308
10 years in 1952, and in that time,

246
00:10:19.308 --> 00:10:21.744
they had never been able to have children.

247
00:10:21.744 --> 00:10:24.542
And they felt that they better take the steps

248
00:10:24.542 --> 00:10:27.047
for adoption, because they really wanted a family.

249
00:10:28.283 --> 00:10:29.513
One of the things that really appealed

250
00:10:29.513 --> 00:10:31.195
to my mother about Catholicism

251
00:10:31.195 --> 00:10:33.827
was the emphasis on Mary.

252
00:10:33.827 --> 00:10:35.367
Because of course she was going through a time

253
00:10:35.367 --> 00:10:37.019
in her life where she was struggling with the issue

254
00:10:37.019 --> 00:10:39.257
of motherhood, she wanted so much to be a mother,

255
00:10:39.257 --> 00:10:41.187
and here was this mother figure.

256
00:10:42.115 --> 00:10:43.709
My mother prayed, asking that she be

257
00:10:43.709 --> 00:10:45.475
granted a child of her own.

258
00:10:45.475 --> 00:10:46.565
And saying too that

259
00:10:46.565 --> 00:10:48.301
if that was not in God's will,

260
00:10:48.301 --> 00:10:50.319
she would gladly adopt a child

261
00:10:50.319 --> 00:10:51.831
and do everything she could to

262
00:10:51.831 --> 00:10:53.985
be a good mother to the adopted child.

263
00:10:54.489 --> 00:10:56.143
Well after she said the prayer,

264
00:10:56.143 --> 00:10:58.271
my mother felt as if a real weight

265
00:10:58.271 --> 00:11:00.036
had been lifted from her that she had placed

266
00:11:00.036 --> 00:11:01.827
her problem in the hands of Mary,

267
00:11:01.827 --> 00:11:04.291
and in turn in the hands of God.

268
00:11:04.291 --> 00:11:06.363
Well, nine months to the date

269
00:11:06.363 --> 00:11:09.345
from that prayer, I was born.

270
00:11:10.100 --> 00:11:12.900
Now, I don't remember exactly when my mother told me

271
00:11:12.900 --> 00:11:15.252
this story, but I was quite young,

272
00:11:15.252 --> 00:11:18.304
and it has imbued my life with

273
00:11:18.304 --> 00:11:20.458
sort of a sweet sense of mysticism.

274
00:11:20.458 --> 00:11:23.148
A sense that there really is power out there,

275
00:11:23.148 --> 00:11:26.256
that there really is a spiritual world.

276
00:11:26.256 --> 00:11:28.104
And that in fact my very life

277
00:11:28.104 --> 00:11:30.611
is a product of that power.

278
00:11:30.611 --> 00:11:33.327
(gentle music)

279
00:11:33.327 --> 00:11:34.529
<v Voiceover>There are times when miracle stories</v>

280
00:11:34.529 --> 00:11:37.777
seem to carry their own badge of proof.

281
00:11:37.777 --> 00:11:39.431
When circumstantial evidence

282
00:11:39.431 --> 00:11:41.781
shows that something incredible happened.

283
00:11:41.781 --> 00:11:43.741
But other times, they don't.

284
00:11:44.023 --> 00:11:46.121
Authors like Joan Wester Anderson

285
00:11:46.121 --> 00:11:47.748
and Paul Robert Walker

286
00:11:47.748 --> 00:11:50.099
hear many reports of miracles.

287
00:11:50.099 --> 00:11:52.283
How do they know these stories aren't just

288
00:11:52.283 --> 00:11:54.607
fabrications, or fantasies?

289
00:11:54.607 --> 00:11:57.939
<v ->I look for the authenticity of the person.</v>

290
00:11:57.939 --> 00:12:00.851
What is this person's life been like

291
00:12:00.851 --> 00:12:02.641
since this happened?

292
00:12:02.641 --> 00:12:04.295
Have they changed?

293
00:12:04.295 --> 00:12:06.402
Have the people around them changed

294
00:12:06.402 --> 00:12:08.864
as a result of what they're doing?

295
00:12:08.864 --> 00:12:10.516
<v ->Does this person have anything to gain</v>

296
00:12:10.516 --> 00:12:13.064
by fabricating this story?

297
00:12:13.064 --> 00:12:14.352
You know it's kind of like

298
00:12:14.352 --> 00:12:16.620
what would be the point of making up this story?

299
00:12:16.620 --> 00:12:18.638
But then, when we get into the process

300
00:12:18.638 --> 00:12:21.268
and I start looking at corrections,

301
00:12:21.268 --> 00:12:23.396
I'm always looking to see,

302
00:12:23.396 --> 00:12:25.944
are the suggestions they're making,

303
00:12:25.944 --> 00:12:28.408
do they seem to be looking to correct the story

304
00:12:28.408 --> 00:12:31.908
for accuracy, or to make it a better story?

305
00:12:31.908 --> 00:12:33.406
Now again and again, I found,

306
00:12:33.406 --> 00:12:35.710
that the people with whom I was working

307
00:12:35.710 --> 00:12:37.504
were making corrections that in my mind

308
00:12:37.504 --> 00:12:39.798
sometimes made it

309
00:12:39.798 --> 00:12:41.842
somewhat less good of a story,

310
00:12:41.842 --> 00:12:43.662
if I were just making up a story.

311
00:12:43.662 --> 00:12:45.708
<v ->And then I go forward and try to find</v>

312
00:12:45.708 --> 00:12:48.478
corroborating testimony for it.

313
00:12:48.478 --> 00:12:51.056
I don't usually do that until after I've

314
00:12:51.680 --> 00:12:53.864
gone through this process of discernment

315
00:12:53.864 --> 00:12:55.210
about the person.

316
00:12:55.210 --> 00:12:57.644
From that point on, the story becomes

317
00:12:57.644 --> 00:12:59.772
the property of the reader.

318
00:12:59.772 --> 00:13:01.844
And the reader can decide

319
00:13:01.844 --> 00:13:04.784
whether he or she wants to believe the story or not.

320
00:13:04.784 --> 00:13:07.472
I think it's very important to chronicle

321
00:13:07.472 --> 00:13:09.684
what is going on today.

322
00:13:09.684 --> 00:13:12.876
And it isn't necessary to say,

323
00:13:12.876 --> 00:13:14.304
"That was a miracle,

324
00:13:14.304 --> 00:13:16.740
"this was just a nice coincidence,

325
00:13:16.740 --> 00:13:19.986
"this was important, this isn't."

326
00:13:21.136 --> 00:13:23.320
<v Voiceover>Stories of miracles sometimes appear</v>

327
00:13:23.320 --> 00:13:25.616
to defy the laws of nature.

328
00:13:25.616 --> 00:13:27.632
But one man, Rodney Kephart,

329
00:13:27.632 --> 00:13:30.740
found himself in a strange no-man's-land

330
00:13:30.740 --> 00:13:33.538
of invisible forces 50 years ago.

331
00:13:34.016 --> 00:13:36.312
Caught between two great powers.

332
00:13:36.312 --> 00:13:38.216
Pitted in a historic drama

333
00:13:38.216 --> 00:13:40.008
that would soon unfold for him

334
00:13:40.008 --> 00:13:42.386
in a most unexpected way.

335
00:13:48.100 --> 00:13:51.712
<v ->I arrived at Wake Island in May of '41</v>

336
00:13:51.712 --> 00:13:55.578
as a carpenter working construction

337
00:13:55.578 --> 00:13:58.096 line:15% 
building an air base.

338
00:13:58.096 --> 00:14:02.296 line:15% 
As you know in 1941 on December the 7th,

339
00:14:02.296 --> 00:14:05.931
the Japanese struck Pearl Harbor.

340
00:14:05.990 --> 00:14:10.990
(dramatic music)

341
00:14:14.776 --> 00:14:18.040
First warning we had was the airport exploded

342
00:14:18.040 --> 00:14:21.596
and then I rushed out onto the

343
00:14:21.596 --> 00:14:24.536
back of the platform where I was working

344
00:14:24.536 --> 00:14:27.280
at the carpenter shop, and I looked up into the eyes

345
00:14:27.280 --> 00:14:30.444
of the Japanese that were strafing us with

346
00:14:30.444 --> 00:14:32.962
.50 caliber machine guns.

347
00:14:33.916 --> 00:14:35.932
<v Voiceover>Immediately following the attack,</v>

348
00:14:35.932 --> 00:14:38.758
Rodney rushed to the hospital to volunteer his help.

349
00:14:39.320 --> 00:14:42.288
<v ->That night, we run 21 patients</v>

350
00:14:42.288 --> 00:14:45.704
through surgery between nine and one in the morning.

351
00:14:45.704 --> 00:14:49.260
Everything from amputations to shrapnel removal,

352
00:14:49.260 --> 00:14:52.592
and the next morning when I was relieved

353
00:14:52.592 --> 00:14:56.512
I began to look for a place to take some rest,

354
00:14:56.512 --> 00:14:59.396
and there was a room at the end of the corridor

355
00:14:59.396 --> 00:15:02.280
that had two empty beds in it.

356
00:15:02.280 --> 00:15:06.118
And at that point, I approached the room

357
00:15:06.118 --> 00:15:09.530
and it seemed to be extremely light in the room,

358
00:15:09.588 --> 00:15:12.724
and as I approached the door I just seemed

359
00:15:12.724 --> 00:15:15.944
to lose my momentum to go forward,

360
00:15:15.944 --> 00:15:18.268
and there seemed to be a personal force

361
00:15:18.268 --> 00:15:20.370
standing in the doorway

362
00:15:20.370 --> 00:15:22.524
to prevent me from entering,

363
00:15:22.524 --> 00:15:25.324
because I had tried three times to enter,

364
00:15:25.324 --> 00:15:29.106
and the same thing, I couldn't

365
00:15:29.106 --> 00:15:31.566
just couldn't proceed.

366
00:15:32.296 --> 00:15:35.442
(heavenly music)

367
00:15:35.442 --> 00:15:39.558
So, I just felt I better go on down to my barracks

368
00:15:39.558 --> 00:15:42.302
even though it was a half a mile walk

369
00:15:42.302 --> 00:15:45.436
and try to get some rest down there.

370
00:15:45.494 --> 00:15:47.146
<v Voiceover>Exhausted and confused,</v>

371
00:15:47.146 --> 00:15:49.414
Rodney walked back to his own barracks,

372
00:15:49.414 --> 00:15:52.056
giving no further thought to the bizarre incident.

373
00:15:52.056 --> 00:15:53.932
Until he put it together with what he saw

374
00:15:53.932 --> 00:15:55.694
the next morning.

375
00:15:56.312 --> 00:16:00.512
<v ->The Japanese just raided us again and</v>

376
00:16:00.512 --> 00:16:04.348
they dropped an incendiary bomb in the hospital,

377
00:16:04.348 --> 00:16:06.336
it dropped in the room where I had chosen

378
00:16:06.336 --> 00:16:09.862
to go to sleep, and that burned the hospital.

379
00:16:12.272 --> 00:16:14.290
<v Voiceover>Rodney feels that his life was saved</v>

380
00:16:14.290 --> 00:16:16.976
by the unexplainable force which had prevented him

381
00:16:16.976 --> 00:16:19.522
from stepping into that ill-fated room.

382
00:16:22.158 --> 00:16:24.732
<v ->So that looks like one of the reasons</v>

383
00:16:24.732 --> 00:16:27.420
that I'm here today to be able to talk to you,

384
00:16:27.420 --> 00:16:29.718
because my life was spared

385
00:16:29.718 --> 00:16:30.426
by that miracle.

386
00:16:30.426 --> 00:16:35.296
(gentle music)

387
00:16:51.472 --> 00:16:52.704
<v Voiceover>Scholars discuss miracles</v>

388
00:16:52.704 --> 00:16:56.260
in the light of contemporary scientific reasoning.

389
00:16:56.260 --> 00:16:58.304 line:15% 
<v ->From about the 15th or 16th Century on</v>

390
00:16:58.304 --> 00:17:00.574 line:15% 
there began to be a split between

391
00:17:00.574 --> 00:17:02.784 line:15% 
how scientists looked at the world as this

392
00:17:02.784 --> 00:17:05.024
complicated machine and how religious

393
00:17:05.024 --> 00:17:06.098
moral philosophers were looking for meaning

394
00:17:06.098 --> 00:17:09.400
and values that transcended the purely physical.

395
00:17:09.822 --> 00:17:12.006
And I think that split is now slowly beginning

396
00:17:12.006 --> 00:17:14.946
to heal, scientists are much more aware

397
00:17:14.946 --> 00:17:17.802
of how many presumptions they do have

398
00:17:17.802 --> 00:17:19.650
how much they don't understand,

399
00:17:19.650 --> 00:17:22.450
they've learned a certain amount of humility.

400
00:17:22.450 --> 00:17:24.074
And religious thinkers on the other hand

401
00:17:24.074 --> 00:17:26.454
are trying to understand what they're feeling

402
00:17:26.454 --> 00:17:28.946
and trying to say in terms of what we know

403
00:17:28.946 --> 00:17:31.160
about the universe, and what really is out there

404
00:17:31.160 --> 00:17:34.238
that scientists can tell us makes up reality.

405
00:17:34.238 --> 00:17:35.612
<v Voiceover>Author Paul Robert Walker</v>

406
00:17:35.612 --> 00:17:38.634
comes to his own conclusions about miracles,

407
00:17:38.634 --> 00:17:43.172
based upon his interpretation of scientific research.

408
00:17:43.172 --> 00:17:44.374
<v ->The recent developments in particle physics</v>

409
00:17:44.374 --> 00:17:46.026
are fascinating in this regard,

410
00:17:46.026 --> 00:17:48.714 line:15% 
because they discovered that

411
00:17:48.714 --> 00:17:51.012 line:15% 
the smallest of subatomic particles,

412
00:17:51.012 --> 00:17:53.518 line:15% 
the quark, behaves differently

413
00:17:54.358 --> 00:17:57.384
depending upon the expectations of the observer.

414
00:17:58.170 --> 00:18:00.888
Now what this means is that the universe

415
00:18:00.888 --> 00:18:03.492
is responsive, the physical universe

416
00:18:03.492 --> 00:18:06.354
responds to our own expectations.

417
00:18:07.496 --> 00:18:08.540
Now how much more responsive

418
00:18:08.540 --> 00:18:10.948
might be the non-physical universe?

419
00:18:10.948 --> 00:18:12.908
In a sense, this is what faith is all about,

420
00:18:12.908 --> 00:18:15.484
faith is a willingness to believe

421
00:18:15.484 --> 00:18:17.276
that the universe will indeed respond

422
00:18:17.276 --> 00:18:20.218
to our needs, to our thoughts, to our prayers.

423
00:18:20.218 --> 00:18:22.378 line:15% 
<v ->You know my journey has taken me from</v>

424
00:18:22.378 --> 00:18:25.238 line:15% 
what you might call the more mechanistic approach

425
00:18:25.238 --> 00:18:27.450 line:15% 
that we're taught in medical school, you know,

426
00:18:27.450 --> 00:18:29.802 line:15% 
how to treat a disease, and that it's been

427
00:18:29.802 --> 00:18:32.770
very much of a spiritual jourey

428
00:18:32.770 --> 00:18:36.550
in the sense of realizing people want help living.

429
00:18:36.550 --> 00:18:38.820
It isn't just getting over their disease.

430
00:18:38.820 --> 00:18:42.122
And as I do this, I keep questioning myself.

431
00:18:42.122 --> 00:18:44.950
And part of it is when somebody has a disease

432
00:18:44.950 --> 00:18:48.450
disappear, and you say it's a miracle,

433
00:18:48.450 --> 00:18:50.354
and why I even played with that word

434
00:18:50.354 --> 00:18:53.266
in my first book, Love, Medicine &amp; Miracles

435
00:18:53.266 --> 00:18:56.094
to make people think about what is a miracle?

436
00:18:56.094 --> 00:18:58.438
When someone comes to me with extensive cancer

437
00:18:58.438 --> 00:18:59.820
and we have the path report, and I've operated

438
00:18:59.820 --> 00:19:01.892
on him and I know he isn't cured,

439
00:19:01.892 --> 00:19:04.300
and it's 12 years later he's never had treatment

440
00:19:04.300 --> 00:19:06.682
for cancer, there's no sign of it in his body,

441
00:19:06.682 --> 00:19:08.612
you see is that a miracle?

442
00:19:08.612 --> 00:19:11.729
Or is it something explainable?

443
00:19:11.729 --> 00:19:14.688
Well, I'd say even if we can explain it

444
00:19:14.688 --> 00:19:17.488
it doesn't take it away from miraculous.

445
00:19:17.488 --> 00:19:19.420
<v ->So in that regard, there's always room for miracles,</v>

446
00:19:19.420 --> 00:19:22.306
there's always gonna be things happening

447
00:19:22.306 --> 00:19:24.992
that we don't understand and that we can't explain,

448
00:19:24.992 --> 00:19:26.896
and it doesn't mean that the people who experience

449
00:19:26.896 --> 00:19:28.408
those things are crazy or that they're

450
00:19:28.408 --> 00:19:31.152
religious fanatics, but there are things gonna happen

451
00:19:31.152 --> 00:19:32.860
that we don't understand, and if they strike

452
00:19:32.860 --> 00:19:35.994
you as a miracle, then we need to take that seriously.

453
00:19:36.500 --> 00:19:41.500
(gentle music)

454
00:19:42.324 --> 00:19:44.116
<v Voiceover>One of Jeannie Hunter's facial nerves</v>

455
00:19:44.116 --> 00:19:47.194
was cut during surgery for a tumor in her ear.

456
00:19:47.644 --> 00:19:50.276
As a result, she lost her sensation of taste,

457
00:19:50.276 --> 00:19:52.150
and the hearing in one ear.

458
00:19:53.356 --> 00:19:56.828
Worse yet, Jeannie lost her sense of equilibrium,

459
00:19:56.828 --> 00:19:59.264
and was unable to walk or maintain her balance

460
00:19:59.264 --> 00:20:01.392
for the better part of each day.

461
00:20:02.316 --> 00:20:04.976 line:15% 
<v ->And I significantly changed my lifestyle</v>

462
00:20:04.976 --> 00:20:07.916 line:15% 
to be just on the couch or in bed

463
00:20:07.916 --> 00:20:10.716 line:15% 
for most of the day and most of the evening.

464
00:20:10.716 --> 00:20:15.196
That was not a very acceptable lifestyle

465
00:20:15.196 --> 00:20:17.688
so I consulted with a second physician,

466
00:20:17.688 --> 00:20:20.878
who offered me no more hope.

467
00:20:21.272 --> 00:20:22.980
<v Voiceover>After four years of suffering,</v>

468
00:20:22.980 --> 00:20:25.052
losing her career and marriage

469
00:20:25.052 --> 00:20:28.300
as a result of her inability to function normally,

470
00:20:28.300 --> 00:20:30.510
Jeannie attended a healing service.

471
00:20:31.876 --> 00:20:34.848
<v ->As I was driving to the church,</v>

472
00:20:34.848 --> 00:20:37.546
I heard very clearly the words,

473
00:20:37.546 --> 00:20:39.796
"This can be the last time that you drive

474
00:20:39.796 --> 00:20:42.076
"to the church sick."

475
00:20:42.076 --> 00:20:44.538
And I was getting kind of excited

476
00:20:44.538 --> 00:20:47.725
'cause I knew that was not my fault.

477
00:20:47.725 --> 00:20:49.735
And then when I got to the church

478
00:20:49.735 --> 00:20:51.683
and began to open the door,

479
00:20:51.683 --> 00:20:53.033
I heard the words again,

480
00:20:53.033 --> 00:20:55.045
"This could be the last time you walk through

481
00:20:55.045 --> 00:20:57.023
"this door sick."

482
00:20:57.023 --> 00:21:00.505
Now I sat and listened to her service,

483
00:21:00.505 --> 00:21:03.596
and she talked about the Holy Spirit,

484
00:21:03.596 --> 00:21:05.935
I did not know the power of God

485
00:21:05.935 --> 00:21:07.585
or healing.

486
00:21:07.585 --> 00:21:10.313
And I sat an hour and a half watching her pray

487
00:21:10.313 --> 00:21:11.993
with other people.

488
00:21:11.993 --> 00:21:14.693
The girls that I had friendships with said,

489
00:21:14.693 --> 00:21:17.545
"We'll ask her to pray with you."

490
00:21:17.545 --> 00:21:19.945
So she laid hands on me,

491
00:21:19.945 --> 00:21:22.735
and then the girls who were there to pray with me

492
00:21:22.735 --> 00:21:26.155
prayed and at the same time my prayer was this,

493
00:21:26.155 --> 00:21:30.053
"Father I ask you to either heal me right now

494
00:21:30.053 --> 00:21:32.993
"or let me die, because I have no life."

495
00:21:32.993 --> 00:21:35.635
And then suddenly, everything became enveloped

496
00:21:35.635 --> 00:21:40.045
in a white cloud, just like a fog rolling in,

497
00:21:40.045 --> 00:21:43.253
and I thought they were in this fog with me.

498
00:21:43.253 --> 00:21:45.205
<v Voiceover>Jeannie underwent what she describes</v>

499
00:21:45.205 --> 00:21:47.515
as an out of body experience,

500
00:21:47.515 --> 00:21:50.885
in which she encountered a warm and healing light.

501
00:21:51.535 --> 00:21:53.573
<v ->They had laid me down on the floor</v>

502
00:21:53.573 --> 00:21:55.945
of the church, I saw my legs

503
00:21:55.945 --> 00:21:58.615
that looked like fluorescent light tubes,

504
00:21:58.615 --> 00:22:01.255
now I know at this point that that was

505
00:22:01.255 --> 00:22:04.193
the Holy Spirit moving in and removing illness

506
00:22:04.193 --> 00:22:05.515
from me.

507
00:22:05.515 --> 00:22:07.125
But at that time,

508
00:22:07.125 --> 00:22:08.550
my thoughts were,

509
00:22:08.550 --> 00:22:11.640
"If I'm on the floor,

510
00:22:11.640 --> 00:22:13.202
"what do I look like?"

511
00:22:13.202 --> 00:22:15.032
'Cause I had all the thought processes

512
00:22:15.032 --> 00:22:16.682
that I have right now.

513
00:22:16.682 --> 00:22:19.113
And I was bending over to see

514
00:22:19.113 --> 00:22:21.602
what exactly did I look like,

515
00:22:21.602 --> 00:22:24.120
suddenly from the right

516
00:22:24.120 --> 00:22:27.992
came a pink white light that spilled out

517
00:22:27.992 --> 00:22:30.422
into triangles.

518
00:22:30.422 --> 00:22:32.822
And from the middle of the light,

519
00:22:32.822 --> 00:22:35.850
came the words, "You are healed."

520
00:22:35.850 --> 00:22:38.762
And I read the words and

